      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1427">
               <p>John was the son of <persName>Patrick Middleton</persName> (<date from="1661"
                     to="1736">1661–1736</date>), a Scottish Episcopal priest well known for
                  defending the nonjuring party. John matriculated at
                     <placeName>Edinburgh</placeName> in <date when="1699">1699</date>, and studied
                  medicine with <persName>Archibald Pitcairne</persName>. He moved to
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> after completing his studies, serving as a
                  physician (with a specialization in obstetrics) for over forty years. His sister
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1428.xml"/>Margaret</persName> (d. <date
                     when="1752">1752</date>) was married to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0389.xml"/>George Cheyne</persName>, another well-known
                  physician and author of treatises on health, who lived nearby in
                     <placeName>Bath</placeName>. Middleton first attended <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> when he became seriously ill
                  in <date when="1740-08">Aug. 1740</date>, and became both his personal physician
                  and good friend. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>
                  marked Middleton&apos;s death in <date when="1760-12-16">Dec. 16, 1760</date> with
                  a poetic eulogy. See <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 3 (<date when="1901">1901</date>):
                  14–17.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
